Computación socialmente relevante
Me pregunto si nuestros estudiantes considerarán socialmente relevante lo mismo que nosotros pero, sin haberlo mirado del todo, parece interesante la idea de la <a href="http://www.sociallyrelevantcomputing.org/"> Socially Relevant Computing</a>

<blockquote>
Socially Relevant Computing (SRC) is a unique paradigm in computing introduced by the researchers at the University at Buffalo, Rice University and Microsoft Research. It focuses on the use of computation to solve problems that students are most passionate about.

Socially Relevant Computing (SRC) presents Computer Science as a cutting-edge technological discipline that empowers them to solve problems of personal interest (socially relevant with a "little s"), as well as problems that are important to society at large (socially relevant with a "capital s"). More about SRC is available at Publications section.
</blockquote>

En definitiva, se trata de utilizar como ejemplos y material de prácticas problemas que son importantes para los estudiantes (s minúscula de social) o para toda la sociedad (S mayúscula, en este caso).

Lo vi en <a href="http://www.lnds.net/2009/04/la-computacion-como-una-ciencia-social.html">La computación como una ciencia social</a>, aunque ese título creo que no refleja bien la idea.

